aItalian cinema gave rise to a number of the best-known films of the postwar years, from Rome Open City to Bicycle Thieves. Although some neorealist film-makers would have preferred to abolish stars altogether, the public adored them and producers needed their help in relaunching the national film industry. This book explores the many conflicts that arose in Italy between 1945 and 1953 over stars and stardom, offering intimate studies of the careers of both well-known and less familiar figures, shedding new light on the close relationship forged between cinema and society during a time of political transition and shifting national identities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCelebritieszItalyvCase studies. 0aFamexSocial aspectszItaly. 0aMotion picture actors and actresseszItalyvBiography. 0aMotion pictureszItalyxHistoryy20th century. 0aRealism in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  abicycle thieves.  aconflicts over stars and stardom.  aintimate studies of careers.  aitalian cinema.  aless familiar figures.  aneorealist film makers.  apolitical transition.  arelationship between cinema and society.  arelaunching national film industry.  arome open city.  ashifting national identities.  awell known stars.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311099772940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781789200027?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781789200027423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781789200027/original  a978-3-11-099772-9  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_MUAR  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_MUAR  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  